2) Clustering and cell type annotation

2025-01-24

This script integrates the samples into a UMAP graph and estimates clusters. Marker genes are calculated for each cluster to help annotate the cell types they represent. The clustering resolution can be adjusted based on the desired level of granularity, allowing either a rough or a more detailed cell-type annotation.

Setup

#Load helper functions
source("/people/nrq364/NeuSiC/scRNA_helper_new.R")

library(magrittr)
library(dplyr)
library(conos)
library(pagoda2)
library(qs)
library(ggplot2)
library(ggrastr)

1. Read in data

Read in filtered list of cms generated in notebook 1) Pre-processing and QC filtering.

cms <- qread("cms_filtered.qs", nthreads = 10)

2. Embed cells using conos

Create a vector with sample names.

names=c("control_1_",
           "control_2_",
           "control_4_",
           "control_5_",
           "control_6_",
           "control_7_",
          "treated_1_",
           "treated_2_",
           "treated_3_",
         "treated_4_",
           "treated_6_",
           "treated_7_")

Use a helper function (defined in the script scRNA_helper_new.R) to embed cells in a UMAP graph and perform first clustering. This helper function performs pagoda2 preprocessing of each count matrix, then creates a conos object and integrates the samples into one UMAP graph. Alignment strength can be adjusted to force stronger integration of samples.

con <- quickConos(cms,
                  names,
                  n.cores.p2=10,
                  n.cores.con=20, get.tsne = F, alignment.strength=0)

3. Refine clustering

Rerun the leiden clustering algorithm to refine the clusters. Not performed here, just the code is shown.

con$findCommunities(method = leiden.community, resolution = 4, min.group.size = 50)
con$plotGraph(groups = con$clusters$leiden$groups %>% factor, title="")
table(con$clusters$leiden$groups %>% factor)

Get the clustering factor from conos object.

leiden_number_of_clusters <- con$clusters$leiden$groups %>% factor

Save conos object with final clustering and also the clustering vector.

qsave(leiden_number_of_clusters, "leiden_number_of_clusters.qs")
qsave(con, "con.qs")

4. Cluster marker genes

Get upregulated genes per cluster (=marker genes), use only control cells, because treatment can alter marker gene expression. Use the leiden factor saved above and extract only the ctrl cells.

anno <- con$clusters$leiden$groups %>% factor

In addition to common parameters (p value, p.adj, Z score and M (mean expression)), getDifferentialGenes estimates specificity, precision and expression fraction (sum expression of the gene within the cluster divided by the total expression of this gene). If the append.auc flag is set, it can estimate ROC AUC, but it can take some time. In the context of differential gene expression (DEG) analysis, a z-score indicates how many standard deviations a specific genes expression in treated samples of a particular cell type deviates from the mean expression of that gene across both control and treated samples within the same cluster.

Positive z-score: The gene's expression in treated samples is above the mean.
Negative z-score: The gene's expression in treated samples is below the mean.
head(de_conos$`1`)

Export top 30 genes for users to look at. Ordering by AUC instead of P value gives more genes that are highly expressed in the respective cluster.

lapply(de_conos, function(x) {x %>% arrange(desc(AUC)) %>% head()})

Transform the list of marker genes into one big table by adding the column Clusters. Order by AUC and save csv file with top 30 genes.

library(data.table)
de_conos <- lapply(de_conos, function(x) {x %>% arrange(desc(AUC)) %>% head(30)})

de_table <- rbindlist(de_conos, idcol = "Cluster")

write.csv2(de_table, file = "top30_marker_byAUC.csv")

Possible visulaizations of marker genes

Plot heatmap of top 5 marker genes (by AUC).

plotDEheatmap(con, as.factor(anno_ctrl),de_conos, n.genes.per.cluster = 5, column.metadata=list(samples=con$getDatasetPerCell()), row.label.font.size = 7)

Plot marker genes on UMAP.

#plot one gene
con$plotGraph(gene="Gad2")

#plot many genes
genes <- c("Gad1", "Gad2", "Lhx2", "Ascl1")
plots <- lapply(genes, function(gene) {
  con$plotGraph(gene = gene, title = gene, size = 0.2)
})
cowplot::plot_grid(plotlist = plots)

5.1 Create pagoda for user annotation or data exploration by user

Merge the list of count matrices.

cm <- conos:::mergeCountMatrices(cms,F)
checkDims(cm, con)

Perform pagoda2 processing on merged matrices.

p2 <- basicP2proc(cm, n.cores = 20, n.odgenes = 3e3, nPcs = 50, k = 30, perplexity = 50, log.scale = TRUE, trim = 10, keep.genes = NULL, min.cells.per.gene = 3, min.transcripts.per.cell = 200, get.largevis = F, get.tsne = F, make.geneknn = F)
p2 <- extendedP2proc(p2, organism="mm")
go.env2 <- p2$go.env
p2 <- p2$p2

Add all the cell metadata relevant for you, e.g.depth, mito fraction, batches in which the samples were processed, sequencing batch.

mit_frac <- mitoFraction(con, "mouse")
mit_frac <- as.factor(round(mit_frac, digits=3))
sample <- con$getDatasetPerCell()
seq_batch <- sample
levels(seq_batch) <- c(1,2,3,2,4,5,4,5)
batch2 <- sample
levels(batch2) <- c(1,2,2,2,3,4,3,4)

metadata.listfactors <- list(sample = sample,
                             seq_batch = seq_batch,
                             batch2 = batch2,
                             mit_frac = mit_frac,
                             cluster = leiden)
metadata.forweb <- factorListToMetadata(metadata.listfactors)

Create the web object.

p2.web <- webP2proc(p2, additionalMetadata = metadata.forweb, title = '[user_name] ', go.env = go.env2, make.go.sets = F)

#Add UMAP embedding
p2.web <- addEmbeddingP2Web(p2.web, con)

#Create .bin-file
p2.web$serializeToStaticFast('p2web_user_name.bin',verbose=T)

Preview the web app.

show.app(app=p2.web, name='app')

To share files via webserver 1. copy file to /pub_html/neusic 2. make file readable for external users with chmod 775 3. access the file via URL: http://kkh.bric.ku.dk/p2auto/index.html?fileURL=http://kkh.bric.ku.dk/neusic/p2web_username.bin
